If you want to add a picture inside your letter, you can add the following code into your CSS work skin.
You will need to change the "background-image: url" line, and put there the picture you want to use.

#workskin .letter_img_1 {
  position: absolute;
  bottom: 3%;
  left: 2%;
  width: 22%;
  max-width: 130px;
  overflow: visible;
  z-index: 9;
}

#workskin .letter_img_content_1 {
  width: 100%;
  padding-bottom: 115%;
  background-image: url("https://squidgeimages.s3.us-west-002.backblazeb2.com/2026/04/01/IMG_7034.png");
  background-size: cover;
  background-position: center;
  background-repeat: no-repeat;
  padding-top: 5px;
  box-shadow: 0 6px 15px #00000040;
  transform: rotate(8deg);
}

#workskin .letter_img_content_1::before {
  content: "";
  position: absolute;
  top: -10px;
  left: 25%;
  width: 50%;
  height: 16px;
  background: #ffffff80;
  box-shadow: 0 1px 3px #00000030;
}




To move the picture where you want on your page, change the "bottom" and "left" values in "#workskin .letter_img_1". 


If you want to have a drawing instead, the best is just to have said drawing on a transparent background, so that it looks like it's really on the letter.
In this case, you can get rid of the whole "#workskin .letter_img_content_1::before" section shown just above, since it is what makes the scotch tape appears above pictures.
You should also get rid of "box-shadow: 0 6px 15px #00000040;" line in "#workskin .letter_img_content_1".


As for your HTML for either picture or drawing, you need to add this:
<div class="letter_img_1"><div class="letter_img_content_1"></div></div>

Put it right after the </div> that comes after the end of your text inside the letter. 
